name: ORAN-SC RICAPP
description:
This project develops xApps to support the OSC e2e use cases as well as demo xApps to demonstrate the use of the nearRT RIC platform and xApp SDK.
ORAN-SC RICAPP: O-RAN = Open RAN, RAN = Radio Access Network, SC = software community, RIC = RAN Intelligent Controller (Near real time RIC), APP = application, specifically an xApp that runs on the nearRT RIC

name: ORAN-SC: O-DU High ( Distributed Unit High)
description:
The O-DU High project implements the functionality of L2 layers of a 5G Protocol stack in Stand Alone (SA) mode. The L2 Layers include the 5G NR RLC, 5G NR MAC and 5G NR Scheduler.

5G NR RLC layer provides services for transferring the control and data messages between MAC layer and O-CU (via DU App).

5G NR MAC layer uses the services of the NR physical layer (O-DU Low) to send and receive data on the various logical channels using multiplexing and demultiplexing techniques.

5G NR SCH layer allocates resources in UL and DL for cell and UE based procedures. 5G NR SCH is completely encapsulated within the 5G NR MAC i.e., all interactions of the 5G NR SCH is via the 5G NR MAC.

The O-DU High interacts with O-CU on the F1AP interface, O-DU Low on the FAPI interface, Near RT RIC on the E2AP interface and OAM/non RT RIC/SMO on the O1 interface.

static_analysis_justification:
We have created a new Jenkins job sonarqube for o-du-l2 module under ORAN sandbox.
https://jenkins.o-ran-sc.org/sandbox/view/All/job/o-du-l2-cmake-sonarqube/

There are two issues: 
                1- While this new job compiles o-du-l2 module below error observed:
14:24:40 /w/workspace/o-du-l2-cmake-sonarqube/src/cm/cm_inet.c:128:10: fatal error: netinet/sctp.h: No such file or directory
14:24:40  #include <netinet/sctp.h>

To resolve this libsctp-dev should be installed.

                2- This job could not finish in default 15 mins time, so timeout parameter under build environment should be changed. (tried with 120)

Temporary solution applied:
Above issues resolved by putting below install command in shell script manually.
   sudo apt install -y libsctp-dev
                
For timeout changed timeout variable to 120.


With above changes the job finished successfully and below sonarcloud updated for o-du-l2 module.
https://sonarcloud.io/dashboard?id=o-ran-sc_o-du-l2


NOTE: As of now there is another issue present related to workspace in sandbox 
https://jenkins.o-ran-sc.org/sandbox/view/All/job/o-du-l2-cmake-sonarqube/ws/

name: O-RAN-SC: Operation and Maintenance (OAM)
description:
According to the O-RAN-SC-OAM-Architecture document all ManagedElements (near-real-time-RIC, O-CU-CP, O-CU-UP, O-DU and O-RU) implement the O1-interface.

The O-RAN-OAM-interface specification defines

a NetConf-Server for Configuration Management (CM) and
a http-client for Fault Management (FM), Performance Management (PM) and other events
on each Management-Service-Provider (MnS-Provider) running on the ManagedElement (ME).



The O-RAN-SC-OAM project provides reference implementation according to the O-RAN OAM (WG1) documents. In addition we provide a common MnS-Consumer for development and module test purposes.  The assumption is that the projects for the ManagedElements can concentrate on the more important user-plane.

Of course each project needs its own OAM repo to address the specific needs of the ManagedElement.

name: FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library
description:
This project aims to provide a Node.js module to enable IoT Agent developers to build custom agents for their devices that can easily connect to NGSI Context Brokers (such as Orion).

An IoT Agent is a component that lets groups of devices send their data to and be managed from a FIWARE NGSI Context Broker using their own native protocols. IoT Agents should also be able to deal with security aspects of the FIWARE platform (authentication and authorization of the channel) and provide other common services to the device programmer.

This project is part of FIWARE. For more information check the FIWARE Catalogue entry for the IoT Agents.( https://www.fiware.org/developers/catalogue/ )
sites_https_justification: The project website and repo use GitHub, which supports HTTPS using TLS. There's no separate download URL (use git to download from the repo).

tests_are_added_justification: Tests are added as new functionality is added. This is verified during the pull request code review, ensuring that proper tests are included in the pull request before merging it.

warnings_justification:
The set of tools used for examining code quality are listed in CONTRIBUTING.md.
The project uses eslint is used to look for problems in Javascript. The markdown documentation is scanned with remark and textlint. Docker files are scanned with Hadolint.
warnings_fixed_justification: In general warnings are addressed. In some cases warnings are disabled for specific cases.
warnings_strict_justification: The settings for the warning tools are generally fairly strict.
know_secure_design_justification: The FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library development team has developers who know how to design secure software
know_common_errors_justification: The FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library development team has developers who know how to design secure software
crypto_published_justification:
This application is a microservice which delegates security to other components such as Keyrock or Keystone. These security components use bcrypt to store salted hashed iterated passwords, and https+standard crypto protocols to communicate with users.

Also, this software use the standard nodeJS libraries (express as a web server and requests as a client) to implement https functionalities.
crypto_call_justification: This software relies on well-known libraries implementing cryptographic.
crypto_floss_justification:
The aforementioned libraries use a FLOSS license. https://github.com/expressjs/express/blob/master/LICENSE
https://github.com/request/request/blob/master/LICENSE
crypto_keylength_justification: Cryptographic libraries used by this application and/or the other microservices to which it interacts (Keyrock or Keystone) allow the usage of such minimum key lengths.
crypto_working_justification: FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library doesn’t use any broken cryptographic algorithm.
crypto_pfs_justification: Nothing in the code inhibits or prevents the use of PFS; that is a property of the website's web server.
crypto_random_justification: Cryptographic libraries used by FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library and/or the other microservices to which it interacts (Keyrock or Keystone) use randomized mechanisms.
delivery_unsigned_justification: FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library does not cryptographic hashes in any HTTP unsecure endpoint.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: No such vulnerabilities at this time.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: No such vulnerabilities at this time.
static_analysis_justification: The project uses eslint (https://eslint.org/) for this purpose. This analysis tool is used as part of the default test process used in local development, as well as the continuous integration server
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: eslint specifically looks for common vulnerabilities in JavaScript applications.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: This is vacuously true, since we've had no reports of vulnerabilities that apply to a deployed system.
static_analysis_often_justification: All commits to GitHub are run through Github Actions, which performs a number of static analysis checks
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Not applicable, software written using Javascript
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Instead of embedding run-time assertions, there are many external tests with assertions that are checked during automated testing.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: No issues were found by dynamic analysis.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: FIWARE IoT Agent Node.js Library doesn’t depend on cryptographic algorithms with known vulnerabilities.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Code implements continuous integration based in GitActions. Each time a new pull request is created, the continuous integration system runs the test on it and it is ready to merge only when all tests pass ok. If a problem is found, feedback is provided via GitHub. In addition, several badges on top of the master README.md of the project provide information about the build status in the master branch.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: No valid private credentials appears in public repositories. When some usernames and/or passwords needs to be used, it is never included in repositories and proper mechanism (e.g. Docker secrets) are used at software building and deployment time.
english_justification: All documentation is in English and the project accepts bug reports and comments in English.
